    "body" : "<p>Compile constants <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.28\" rel=\"noreferrer\">can only be primitives and Strings</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>15.28. Constant Expressions</strong></p>\n<p>A compile-time <em>constant expression</em> is an expression denoting a value of primitive type or a String that does not complete abruptly and is composed using only the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Literals of primitive type and literals of type <code>String</code></li>\n<li>Casts to primitive types and casts to type <code>String</code></li>\n<li>[...] operators [...]</li>\n<li>Parenthesized expressions whose contained expression is a constant expression.</li>\n<li>Simple names that refer to constant variables.</li>\n<li>Qualified names of the form <em>TypeName</em> . <em>Identifier</em> that refer to constant variables.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Actually in java there is no way to protect items in an array. At runtime someone can always do <code>FieldValues.FIELD1[0]=&quot;value3&quot;</code>, therefore the array cannot be really constant if we look deeper.</p>\n"
